WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Well, I think users generally like nice things in their packages.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:07.000
But what is nice?

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Here are a few things I want users to think when experiencing niceties in a package.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.000
One is, the maintainer understands that different users can have different needs.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Next one is, the package made something otherwise cumbersome pretty easy to deal with.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Learning how to use the package was a snap, thanks to the great docs.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:30.000
Lastly, the provided datasets are convenient, makes it easy to try out the package.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Now I'll provide examples on how I added nice things to two Python packages, namely pointblank and great tables.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.000
So we'll start with the first one, where the maintainer understands that different users can have different needs.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
First off, let's get a quick introduction to pointblank.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
It's a package for validating tables, like do we have duplicate rows?

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Are cum values in the defined range?

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:52.000
We can find this out.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
We define a validation plan, we can interrogate the data table, and you get a nice report in the end.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
But let's look at line 3 of this pointblank validation code.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Now this is the part I really wanted to make nice, this data parameter.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Many other libraries that accept a table, they tend to support only one or a few types of tables.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:11.000
It gets kind of restrictive.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.000
The problem with this is that if a user uses different types of tables that aren't supported,

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
they are generally less likely to use the package.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
I really wanted to, just like the R version of pointblank, support many types of tables.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.000
This includes a variety of data frames and a plethora of database tables.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
Luckily, I didn't really have to write too much custom code to support each of these table types,

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:40.000
because there are actually two Python libraries that could help make bring your own table pretty painless.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
The implementation uses two nice libraries, narwhals and ibis.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Narwhals can handle all sorts of data frames like polars, pandas, and spark,

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:53.000
and ibis handles a huge number of other types of tables, like many database tables.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
By incorporating these libraries into pointblank,

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
it was actually a cinch to support all the tables that narwhals and ibis can work with.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Supporting all sorts of tables meant that we had to build two internal processing pipelines,

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
one for narwhals and the other for ibis.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
This doubled the amount of code to maintain, but it still felt like a win, because it was so nice for the user.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
We can see in this diagram that the user just has to provide a data table,

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
and the program will handle it in one of two code paths.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
The way it was set up ensured that the user will see the correct results no matter what type of table was used,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
and crucially, the user will get output artifacts in the same format as the input.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Not very long ago, narwhals gained the ability to directly use ibis tables.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
This was amazing, since it meant that pointblank, with a little work,

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
would no longer need branching code for both narwhals and ibis.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.000
It just goes to show that narwhals is itself a very nice Python package.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Anyway, we jumped at the opportunity to simplify our code,

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
and this is not the only way that narwhals got nicer.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Narwhals gained the ability to use spark dataframes,

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
so pointblank no longer needed a sparkdf to be an ibis table.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
For a spark user, this is so much nicer.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
No need to transform the dataframe before using it in pointblank.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:12.000
In the future, we can go even further by removing the user's need to prepare ibis tables for other table types.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
That concludes the first part.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Let's go on to the second, where I discuss how cumbersome things could be made easier.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Let's now get to know the GreatTables package.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
As the name might imply, it's a package for making tables.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
One could say it's a package for creating beautiful tables for display purposes.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
On the left is a chunk of GreatTables code.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
On the right is a very nice-looking table.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:41.000
It's the kind of table that would look great in a Quora document or in a Shiny app.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Because we are using a dataframe to create a table for display,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.000
we easily run into the problem where dealing with lots of table columns can be a bit tedious for the user.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Some tables just have lots of columns,

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.000
and with the way that GreatTables works,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
we have to often declare column names in order to format values within them,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.000
or to style cells.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
We can always use lists of column names with the GreatTables API.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Here's an example where we are trying to add a column spanner above four different columns.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Notice that the user has to write out in full each of the column names.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.000
It's a lot of typing.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Of course, this is problematic,

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
and we could and should make the experience nicer for users of the package.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:34.000
The solution to this problem was to incorporate the use of Polars column selectors with the GreatTables package.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:39.000
Polars, if you don't know it, is a very nice and performant dataframe library.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.000
The column selectors that they offer are very similar to our TySelect select helper functions.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:49.000
You might have used those if you worked with Tyverse packages like dplyr.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Now, compare the verbose code block with all the column names with the code in the bottom.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Using a selector to reference the common piece of text across all four column names makes for a shorter chunk of GreatTables code,

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
and to me, it's quite a bit more readable, owing to its brevity.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Using Polar selectors in GreatTables is what I would call extra nice.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
If you are coming from GT, which is the R version of GreatTables,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
this is similar to the TySelect helpers used in that package.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Let's compare some bits of TySelect with Polar selectors.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
As you can see in this comparison table, much of the nomenclature is the same.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Sure, everything becomes all in Polars, and by name does the work of two TySelect helper functions,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:42.000
but by and large, these separate implementations of selectors largely use the same naming.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Having selectors available can encourage the use of smart column naming.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.000
Let's have a look at the small table of column name motifs

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:57.000
and how GreatTables code with column selectors can take advantage of certain styles of naming.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:03.000
If you have columns that end with underscore PCT, they are all percentage values,

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
and you'd probably want to format them as such.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Using format percent along with the ends with column selector,

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
we can perform percentage formatting all in one statement.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
Maybe you have columns with count values.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:22.000
One naming convention you can hold to would be prefixing those column names with end underscore.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.000
The GreatTables formatter format integer could be used with the starts with column selector.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
Now all those count columns can be formatted.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:38.000
Specific names like lat and lon for latitude and longitude could get the format number treatment.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:43.000
Just use the by name select helper to programmatically pass in those columns.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
Styling in GreatTables can also take advantage of Polar's column selectors.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
Columns that begin with ID underscore are understood as ID values.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
The tapStyle method requires locations as a parameter,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.000
and if you want to target body cells, you can use locBody.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:02.000
That itself has a columns parameter,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:07.000
and we can pass in starts with along with the ID underscore text fragment.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
All your ID columns will then be styled.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
In this example, we set the font as monospace, but you can do anything you want.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
I just want to conclude this whole section, section 2,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.000
by saying that having to enter a ton of column names is not nice.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
Using column selectors? Very nice.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:29.000
On top of that, having some consistency with the R version of GreatTables,

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.000
and I'm talking about GT,

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:36.000
lowers the switching cost if you're coming from R and then going to Python.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
The next section, section 3,

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.000
is all about making the documentation great in the project website.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:46.000
This is a nice thing to do because it may elicit the response,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
learning how to use the package was a snap thanks to the great docs.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
This slice of nice is all about making a nice project website.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
The challenge with the Pointblank API was the bigness of it all.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:04.000
It has 7 classes, 41 methods, and 25 functions.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
Not exactly a small package, to say the least.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.000
So making the documentation nice for first-time users and returning users is essential.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
And docs are totally my bag, so I was fired up to make them nice anyway.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
I wanted to make four really nice corners of the project website.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:31.000
They are the user guide, the examples gallery, the API reference, and the Point blog.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:34.000
And I had goals for each of these sections.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:38.000
For the user guide, I really wanted to have a treasure trove of useful information.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:42.000
And having tons of info is useless unless you have instructional chops.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
We used a spiral sequence to introduce large topics

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
and then cover bits of those topics in subsequent sections.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:54.000
Finally, links from the user guide to the appropriate parts of the API reference were deemed essential.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:00.000
We wanted to build out an examples gallery with tons of examples that are easy to understand,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
aren't text-heavy, and cover a lot of ground.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
The API reference had to be nicer than nice.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
I wanted it to be comprehensive, have wonderful examples,

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
and I wanted each article to be easy to navigate.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Finally, the Point blog.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
It's really a blog, and the goals were to keep things interesting,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:24.000
post often, and have it provide insights that the rest of the docs don't really have.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
We continuously improved the Point Blank user guide.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:33.000
It can start off being small, but now has 26 pages.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
As I mentioned before, we embraced the spiral sequence.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
What that does is to balance introductory breadth with subsequent depth.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.000
Put another way, what we do in practice is introduce parts of a large concept

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
and then break it down in small sections.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.000
As the name of the game with user guides is continuous improvement,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
we kept improving on the quality of the examples provided.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
The examples typically consist of code, output, and usually both.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:03.000
We tried to place the example early in each new section.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:08.000
To make it really nice, we show you the actual output you'll see in your own environment.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
The Point Blank website has a gallery of examples.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
We now have 25 examples, and they cover a wide range of use cases.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
To make the examples gallery the best it can be,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
in other words, really, really nice, we followed a particular style.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
First, we kept exposition down to a minimum.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
The code and output was the focus of each example page.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
Secondly, we flipped the example around and presented the output first,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
and then the code needed to produce that output.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:42.000
This is nice because you start each example page with an interesting visual.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
Next, we wanted to reduce any sort of example noise,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:51.000
so any code statements that didn't serve a purpose for teaching the main concept of the example were eliminated.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
We did provide code comments in the example code.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
They're usually off to the side, and they are mainly for clarifying the code.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
We also provided a preview table of the input data table,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:05.000
and that's at the bottom of each example page and initially hidden.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:11.000
The API documentation part of the website has been overhauled to add more structure.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
We were able to make quite a few improvements over the defaults.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:19.000
The first is a visual indicator that shows us whether we're looking at documentation for a class,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
a method, or a function.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:27.000
The summary line just below that gives readers quick info on what the class, method, or function does.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:34.000
The usage information is displayed next, and under that, we put one or more description paragraphs underneath.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
Any further information is typically provided as special sections further down in the doc.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:45.000
The parameter section, since it has very important information, is clearly marked with an outline.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
The example section has even more prominent styling.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
This is helpful for getting a sense of place,

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
as one might scroll quickly toward the bottom of the doc where the example section is placed.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
Pointblank has a blog on the package website,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
and actually GreatTables has a blog on its own package website.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
Blogs for a single package are nice,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:10.000
and since we use Cordo and Cordodoc for the package website, adding a blog is very easy.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
We put up these blogs to keep people informed of new ideas.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
It's also useful just as a place to talk about the subject that the package is trying to address.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
So in the Point blog, we've covered topics in data validation,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
and in the GreatTables blog, we've talked more generally about tables at certain points.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
Well, that's all I wanted to say about making documentation great for a package website.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
Let's move on to the fourth section,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:38.000
and the topic there is adding lots of datasets to a package website.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.000
The topic there is adding lots of datasets to a Python package.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
GreatTables has a lot of datasets.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:48.000
Here they all are.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
There are 16 datasets in total,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
and each one has a decorative medallion.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
Those serve to make the datasets nice and fun.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.000
Having lots of datasets in GreatTables means we can provide great examples with them.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
For example, if I wanted to show a super text-heavy table,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
I would use the Peeps dataset.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
If the demonstration involves adding graphics to the table,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
then I would likely use the Metro dataset.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:19.000
I use the formatImage method to get those SVG graphics into the table cells.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
If I wanted to show users how to make nanoplots,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
I would probably reach for the Illness dataset.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
And as a final example on how datasets make for nice examples,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:33.000
I like the Films dataset when showing tables with country flag icons within them.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
From what I've seen, not too many Python packages include data.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Nevertheless, I still think it's nice to have them.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
And there's no real convention for datasets in Python packages,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
both in the including part and in the consuming part.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.000
In terms of dataset access, we did things a little differently in GreatTables and PointBlank.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
Both are nice, I just want to point them both out

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:58.000
in case you want to try including datasets in your own Python package.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
In GreatTables, we expose a data module.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
The user would then import any dataset needed.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
This is easy for the user and great for the docs

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
as each dataset would get its own documentation page.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
In PointBlank, it's a little different.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
That package provides the loadDataset function.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
You can choose from multiple datasets and output table types with that function.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
Again, there's no real conventions for datasets in Python packages,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
but both these approaches are nice enough.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Providing a selection of datasets in a package is good for users in other ways.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
One way it helps a lot is when experimenting with the API.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
It's something of a pain to create your own data frames

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
on account of all the typing you have to do

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
for what is essentially throwaway experimentation code.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
A good pattern instead is to draw from a set of datasets

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
and pick one close to your immediate needs.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
You might trim it down a bit before testing it out, but it's a good pattern.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
With GreatTables, a user might use the ExhibitDataset

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
to test out formatting methods.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
It's small and the rendered table will easily fit on a screen.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
If you want to make a table that takes advantage of categorical value columns,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
you might use the PizzaPlaceDataset.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
It's a big dataset, representing an entire year of pizza sales from a pizza place.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
For that reason, the user might just want one slice of it.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
As a final example of a dataset that's nice and useful for the user,

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.000
the PhotolysisDataset is great if you want to experiment with nanoplots.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Well, that's really everything I wanted to say about datasets.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
They are good to have and really add a lot to a Python package.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.000
I'm all done with the examples on how I added niceties to two Python packages.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
Let's move on to some closing notes right now.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
Having lots of nice things in a Python package

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
will probably be appreciated by your users.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
As for myself, I'll keep on improving the packages I work on.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
There are real benefits to making packages nice.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
There can be lowered friction for the user,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
where many small conveniences can go a long way.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
Users may get productive faster.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.000
Whenever you can reduce boilerplate, people will get meaningful results sooner.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.000
If you have nice docs and datasets, you might not have to address as many issues.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
Things will just be more clear for the user.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:15.000
And lastly, a strong set of nice qualities will lead to stronger credibility for the project

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
and likely better discovery.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
After all, the package will be easier to showcase

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
and easier for others to recommend.

